l influence on their emerging cultural and intellectual trends. This book, the first comparative study of its kind, follows the Benedictine Order over eleven centuries, from their early diaspora to the challenge of continental reformation. JAMES G. CLARK is Professor of History, University of Exeter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMonasticism and religious ordersxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBenedictines.  aChristian Communities.  aChristianity.  aChurch.  aCultural Influence.  aCultural influence.  aLatin.  aMedieval Europe.  aMiddle Ages.  aMonastic Orders.  aMonastic order.  aReligious order.  aSocial Organization.  aSocial organization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615947340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846159473423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846159473/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles